<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBFD0D7A58FCB7" bold="true" box="[199,381,762,787]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Measurements.</emphasis>
<typeStatus id="467D4487FFEE933CBD88FD0D7AC9FCB7" box="[388,492,762,787]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Holotype</typeStatus>
male: Body length: 
<quantity id="5E3E57C0FFEE933CBEDDFD0C7802FCB6" box="[721,807,763,787]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity id="5E3E57C0FFEE933CBF39FD0C78A9FCB6" box="[821,908,763,787]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" unit="mm" value="7.4">7.4 mm</quantity>
including wings); forewing length: 
<quantity id="5E3E57C0FFEE933CB92CFD0D7EA2FCB6" box="[1312,1415,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.15" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" unit="mm" value="6.15">6.15 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D1DCA9AEFFEE933CBCCBFCE97956FC62" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBFCE97956FC62" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBFCE97A1FFC93" bold="true" box="[199,314,798,823]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="5EC681A6FFEE933CBD44FCE9790FFC92" authority="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[328,554,798,822]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Amazobenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBD44FCE9790FFC92" box="[328,554,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Amazobenna pennyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B0819B4CFFEE933CBE3EFCE979AEFC93" box="[562,651,798,823]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" rank="species">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBE3EFCE979AEFC93" bold="true" box="[562,651,798,823]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be promptly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="5EC681A6FFEE933CB826FCE87F90FC92" authorityName="Penny" authorityYear="1980" box="[1066,1205,798,822]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Amazobenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CB826FCE87F90FC92" box="[1066,1205,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">A. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the general color of the wing and body. In addition, the genitalia are quite distinct, having the characteristic slender anal segment with triangular apex in posterior view, and genital style widening distally with truncated apex, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="5EC681A6FFEE933CB93FFC907EB9FCDA" authority="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[1331,1436,871,894]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Amazobenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CB93FFC907E61FCDA" box="[1331,1348,871,894]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CB95DFC907EB9FCDA" box="[1361,1436,871,894]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">pennyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBC9BFC7D7BD5FC07" bold="true" box="[151,240,906,931]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B0819B4CFFEE933CBC9BFC7D7BD5FC07" box="[151,240,906,931]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the anal segment is broad with a trapezoidal apex in posterior view, and the genital style is narrow distally, widened in the basal 2/3, with round apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D1DCA9AEFFEE933CBCCBFC257E34F9A3" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" type="description">
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBFC257847FB3B" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBFC257A7CFC4F" bold="true" box="[199,345,978,1003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Description.</emphasis>
Coloration. General body color yellow (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CBF37FC2578EFFC4F" box="[827,970,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1935,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 19. Habitus, lateral view; 20. Head, anterior view; 21. Antenna, lateral view; 22. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 23. Abdominal process, lateral view. Scale bars: 1= 1mm; 2,4 = 0.5mm; 3 = 0.3 mm; 5 = 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632453/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Figs. 19–23</figureCitation>
). Forewing yellowish, semihyaline with brown oval spot in apical portion of clavus extending to first cubital cell (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CBFDDFC017F00FBAB" box="[977,1061,1014,1039]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–29" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1976,1999]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,1618,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[188,1398,1618,1955]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 28–29. Wings of Amazobenna Penny species. 28. Amazobenna reticulata Penny (male); 29. A. pennyi sp. nov. (male). Scale bars: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632459/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
); long, narrow, brown, transverse band extending from the vein M5 to apex of pterostigma; narrow brown stripes covering base of medial, cubital and anal veins; narrow brown stripes covering radial and median veins at apex of wing; anterior cubital vein covered by brown stripe and small pale-brown spot at apex of CuA2. Pterostigma whitish-yellow. Hindwing yellowish, semihyaline. Genital style pale-brown (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CBEC7FB717870FB3B" box="[715,853,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1454,1477]" captionTargetBox="[198,1403,193,1417]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1403,193,1442]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 24. Male terminalia, lateral view; 25. Male terminalia, posterior view; 26. Anal segment, pygofer, medioventral process and genital style, lateral view. 27. Anal segment, pygofer, medioventral process and genital style, posterior view. Abbreviations: anal seg, anal segment; pyg, pygofer; medven proc, medioventral process; genital sty, genital style. Scale bars: 6,8 = 0.2 mm; 7,9 = 0,3 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632457/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Figs. 24–25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBFB5D7895FA8B" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
Head: median carina of frons weakly marked (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CBEC2FB5D7807FB67" box="[718,802,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1935,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 19. Habitus, lateral view; 20. Head, anterior view; 21. Antenna, lateral view; 22. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 23. Abdominal process, lateral view. Scale bars: 1= 1mm; 2,4 = 0.5mm; 3 = 0.3 mm; 5 = 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632453/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
); pedicellus as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CB865FB5D7F99FB67" box="[1129,1212,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1935,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 19. Habitus, lateral view; 20. Head, anterior view; 21. Antenna, lateral view; 22. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 23. Abdominal process, lateral view. Scale bars: 1= 1mm; 2,4 = 0.5mm; 3 = 0.3 mm; 5 = 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632453/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Thorax: pronotum somewhat emarginated; median and lateral longitudinal carinae of mesonotum weakly marked, median carina not reaching posterior margin of mesonotum, lateral carinae not reaching anterior margin of mesonotum (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CB934FB057EB5FAAF" box="[1336,1424,1266,1291]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1935,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,369,1871]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 19. Habitus, lateral view; 20. Head, anterior view; 21. Antenna, lateral view; 22. Head and thorax, dorsal view; 23. Abdominal process, lateral view. Scale bars: 1= 1mm; 2,4 = 0.5mm; 3 = 0.3 mm; 5 = 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632453/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Legs: hindtibia with 7 apical spines; hindtarsus with 8+8 apical spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBFACD7E34F9A3" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="01FDE6A0FFEE933CBD76FACD7923FAF7" box="[378,518,1338,1363]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1454,1477]" captionTargetBox="[198,1403,193,1417]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1403,193,1442]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Amazobenna pennyi sp. nov., holotype: 24. Male terminalia, lateral view; 25. Male terminalia, posterior view; 26. Anal segment, pygofer, medioventral process and genital style, lateral view. 27. Anal segment, pygofer, medioventral process and genital style, posterior view. Abbreviations: anal seg, anal segment; pyg, pygofer; medven proc, medioventral process; genital sty, genital style. Scale bars: 6,8 = 0.2 mm; 7,9 = 0,3 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2632457/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Figs. 24–27</figureCitation>
): anal segment elongate and wide, only slightly longer than wide in dorsal view, dorsal margin almost straight, ventral margin abruptly produced ventrally at apex in lateral view, apex trapezoidal in posterior view. Pygofer with lateral lobe well produced, apex round in lateral view, parallel in ventral view. Medioventral process of pygofer conical in lateral view, with posterior margin triangular in ventral view. Genital style narrowed distally, widening in the basal 2/3 on outer margin, inner margin almost straight, parallel in ventral aspect, with apex round, divergent in posterior view. Aedeagus with straight shaft bearing long spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D1DCA9AEFFEE933CBCCBF9E578AEF9EB" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBF9E578AEF9EB" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBF9E57A6BF98F" bold="true" box="[199,334,1554,1579]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named to honor Dr. Norman D. Penny, who created this genus, for his immense contribution to the knowledge of invertebrate fauna in the Amazon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D1DCA9AEFFEE933CBCCBF9AD798EF9D7" box="[199,683,1626,1651]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBF9AD798EF9D7" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" box="[199,683,1626,1651]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBF9AD7A7CF9D7" bold="true" box="[199,345,1626,1651]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry id="E1D1BAB5FFEE933CBD6BF9AD7A8EF9D7" box="[359,427,1626,1651]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Amazonas) (Fig. 30).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D1DCA9AEFFEE933CBCCBF9897931F8A7" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9979FA25FFEE933CBCCBF9897931F8A7" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCCBF9897A69F933" bold="true" box="[199,332,1662,1687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">Discussion.</emphasis>
Previously, the 
<typeStatus id="467D4487FFEE933CBE06F988791FF933" box="[522,570,1663,1687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="5EC681A6FFEE933CBE93F9887808F932" authorityName="Penny" authorityYear="1980" box="[671,813,1662,1686]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Amazobenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBE93F9887808F932" box="[671,813,1662,1686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">A. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the only known species included into the genus. Since 
<taxonomicName id="5EC681A6FFEE933CBCEDF9547A75F91E" authority="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Viegas &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[225,336,1699,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Amazobenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBCEDF9547A75F91E" box="[225,336,1699,1722]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">A. pennyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B0819B4CFFEE933CBD50F9557A9EF91F" box="[348,443,1698,1723]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567" rank="species">
<emphasis id="ABB22637FFEE933CBD50F9557A9EF91F" bold="true" box="[348,443,1698,1723]" pageId="6" pageNumber="567">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
fits very well to the generic description, we consider both species congeneric. The discovery of a further species for this genus allowed us to verify that the diagnostic characters used by 
<bibRefCitation id="FD5787D4FFEE933CB95AF9307BC4F8A7" author="Penny, N. D." pageId="6" pageNumber="567" pagination="207 - 212" refId="ref4455" refString="Penny, N. D. (1980) A revision of American Bennini (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Cixiidae). Acta Amazonica, 10 (1), 207 - 212. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 1809 - 43921980101207" type="journal article" year="1980">Penny (1980)</bibRefCitation>
to describe it remain valid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
